               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1191" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1191" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1191" type="surname" value="PERKINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1191" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN PERKINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Field-lane. The prisoner lodged in the same house with me—on the 12th of June I lost a pair of my wife's boots, and a pair my own—these are them—they are called high-lows, or shoes—I saw them the night before, when I went to bed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1192" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1192" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1192" type="surname" value="BARRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1192" type="given" value="ELLEN"></interp>ELLEN BARRY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Field-lane. On the 12th of June I saw the pri<lb></lb>soner at the pawnbroker's, offering some boots there for 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I told the pawn<lb></lb>broker to detain the boots, as I thought I knew them—I fetched the prose<lb></lb>cutor's wife, and while I was gone the prisoner went away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I am quite positive I was not in the shop. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I am sure it was you—these are the boots he offered—I took very great notice of them, from the toes to the heels, when I had seen the prosecutor's wife wear them for about ten days.</p>
               <p>
